1293":"1240–1293","1235–Female":"1235–Deceased","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1203–Male":"1203–Deceased","1208–Female":"1208–Deceased","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1208":"1208","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cumbe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Michel.","Scottish (Midlothian and East Lothian): from Gaelic <b>Mac Thom</b> ‘son of <i>Thom</i>’, see   Thomas  . It is also a shortened form of   McCombe  .","English: variant of   Coombe  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thomas","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Breton, German, Dutch, Flemish, Danish, Greek, West Indian (mainly Haiti and Jamaica), and African (mainly Tanzania and Nigeria): from the personal name <i>Thomas</i>, of Biblical (New Testament) origin, from Aramaic <i>t’ōm’a</i>, a byname meaning ‘twin’. It was borne by one of the disciples of Christ, known for his scepticism about Christ's resurrection (John 20:24–29). The <i>Th-</i> spelling is organic, the initial letter of the name in the Greek New Testament being a theta. The English pronunciation as <i>t</i> rather than <i>th-</i> is the result of French influence from an early date. In Britain, the surname is widely distributed throughout the country, but especially common in Wales and Cornwall. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (e.g. Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Toma   and   Tuma  , Albanian   Toma   and   Thoma  , and Slavic surnames listed in 3 below), and their patronymics and other derivatives (e.g. Polish   Tomaszewski   and Slovenian <b>Tomažič</b>; see   Tomazic  ). In France, this surname is most common in the Vosges and Brittany. The name <i>Thomas</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Machan  ,   Mammen  , and   Oommen  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Native American (e.g. Navajo): adoption of the English personal name <i>Thomas</i> (see 1 above) as a surname.","Germanized or Americanized form of Polish   Tomas  , <b>Tomasz</b>, and <b>Tomaś</b>, Sorbian <b>Tomaš</b> (see also 4 below), Croatian <b>Tomaš</b> and   Tomas  , Slovenian <b>Tomaš</b> and <b>Tomaž</b>, Czech and Slovak <b>Tomáš</b>, all meaning ‘Thomas’."]},{"name":"Comeau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Andre, Camille, Alphie, Emile, Fernand, Herve, Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Murielle, Normand.","French:","topographic name from a diminutive of <i>come</i>, a variant of <i>combe</i> ‘narrow valley, ravine’ (see   Combe  )."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon de Cumbe II was born in 1232, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Simon de Cumbe I, was 29 and his mother, Christiane of Wiltshire, was 25. He married Margret de Denton. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1282, in his hometown, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1232–1282":"1232–1282","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1208":"1208","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1232–1282":"1232–1282","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1203–Male":"1203–Kuollut","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1208":"1208","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1232–1282":"1232–1282","1240–1293":"1240–1293","1235–Female":"1235–Décédée","1255–1295":"1255–1295","1203–Male":"1203–Décédé","1208–Female":"1208–Décédée","1203":"1203","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","1232":"1232","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1282":"1282","1293":"1293","1208":"1208","Wiltshire, 